RA.sequence(O.Applicative) lifts the array outward: if any element is None the whole thing is None, otherwise Some of the unwrapped array. Use fp-ts/ReadonlyArray when your inputs are ReadonlyArray.

```typescript
import * as RA from "fp-ts/ReadonlyArray";
import * as O from "fp-ts/Option";
import { pipe } from "fp-ts/function";

const allSome: ReadonlyArray<O.Option<number>> = [O.some(1), O.some(2), O.some(3)];
const withNone: ReadonlyArray<O.Option<number>> = [O.some(1), O.none, O.some(3)];

export const sequenced: O.Option<ReadonlyArray<number>> = pipe(allSome, RA.sequence(O.Applicative));
export const gapped: O.Option<ReadonlyArray<number>> = pipe(withNone, RA.sequence(O.Applicative));
// sequenced -> some([1,2,3]); gapped -> none
```

A.traverse picks its evaluation order from the Applicative instance. TE.ApplicativeSeq runs tasks one at a time so downstream tasks start only after upstream ones resolve. TE.ApplicativePar fires all tasks immediately and collects results. Both short-circuit on the first Left by semantics of Either, but the parallel version has already spent work on sibling tasks.

