A.traverse(T.ApplicativePar) fires every task immediately because Task is just a lazy Promise thunk. The outer Promise settles when all inner ones settle, preserving order.

```typescript
import * as T from "fp-ts/Task";
import * as A from "fp-ts/Array";
import { pipe } from "fp-ts/function";

const sleep = (ms: number, tag: string): T.Task<string> => () =>
  new Promise((res) => setTimeout(() => res(`${tag}@${ms}`), ms));

export const parallel: T.Task<ReadonlyArray<string>> = pipe(
  [sleep(30, "a"), sleep(10, "b"), sleep(20, "c")],
  A.traverse(T.ApplicativePar)((t) => t),
);
```

A Task<A> is a lazy thunk () => Promise<A>: calling the thunk starts the work, and until you call it nothing has happened. That laziness is what makes Task a referentially transparent value, unlike a Promise which eagerly starts on creation. You pick Task when you want to describe async computations as plain values, compose them with map and chain, and defer execution to the program edge.

```typescript
import * as T from "fp-ts/Task";
import { pipe } from "fp-ts/function";

const fetchA: T.Task<string> = () => Promise.resolve("A");
const fetchB = (a: string): T.Task<string> => () => Promise.resolve(`${a}->B`);

export const program: T.Task<string> = pipe(
  fetchA,
  T.chain(fetchB),
  T.map((s) => `done:${s}`),
);
```

T.delay wraps a Task so its underlying Promise resolves only after a timer elapses. T.ap combines two Tasks applicatively: the lifted function waits for its argument Task to settle. Because both sides run in parallel (Task is just a lazy Promise thunk), the applicative's total latency is the longer of the two, not the sum.

```typescript
import * as T from "fp-ts/Task";
import { pipe } from "fp-ts/function";

const first: T.Task<string> = pipe(T.of("hello"), T.delay(50));
const second: T.Task<string> = T.of("world");

export const combined: T.Task<string> = pipe(
  first,
  T.map((a) => (b: string) => `${a} ${b}`),
  T.ap(second),
);

export const run = combined();
```

